perf_dt=function(actual,forecast){
  n=length(actual)
  error=actual-forecast
  mean=mean(actual)
  sd=sd(actual)
  FBias=sum(error)/sum(actual)
  MPE=sum(error/actual)/n
  MAPE=sum(abs(error/actual))/n
  RMSE=sqrt(sum(error^2))/n
  MAD=sum(abs(error))/n
  WMAPE=MAD/mean
  l=data.frame(n,mean,sd,FBias,MAPE,RMSE,MAD,WMAPE)
  return(l)
}

4 different algorithms were tried on 4 different datasets. On dataset 1, a binary classification problem was solved, whereas on dataset 2, a multiclass classification class was worked on. The datasets 2 and 3 were regression problems where the target was continous. The weighted mean absolute percentage error (WMAPE) values for each algorithm and dataset are reported above.

For penalized regression approach, different values for the parameter lambda could be tried and WMAPE values could be compared for further analysis

For the decision trees, increasing the complexity parameter or the minimumnumber of observations per tree leaf would probably improve the overall performance of this method, however, this would make computation harder.

The random forest method best in terms of WMAPE in general, when compared to the other 3 methods. Similar to the decision tree increasing the complexity parameter, the minimumnumber of observations per tree leaf or the number of trees per forest would probably improve the overall performance of this method, however, this would make computation harder.

The boosted decision trees gave better performance measures than the regular decision trees. However, the computation time was increased. For further analysis similar parameters and the learning rate in addition could be changed.
